  "prompt": "How long does it take for teeth to relapse (move) after a broken retainer?",
  "response": "The time it takes for teeth to relapse or move after a retainer is broken can vary widely among individuals. Factors that influence this include:\n\n1. **Duration of Orthodontic Treatment**: How long you wore braces or aligners before getting the retainer.\n2. **Type of Retainer**: Fixed retainers may hold teeth in place more effectively than removable ones.\n3. **Duration Without Retainer**: The longer you go without a retainer, the more likely your teeth are to shift. Some people may notice changes within a few days to weeks, while others may take several months.\n4. **Age**: Younger individuals may experience more rapid shifts in tooth position compared to adults.\n5. **Individual Anatomy**: Each person\u2019s dental anatomy and habits (like grinding teeth or thumb sucking) can affect stability.\n\nIt's important to consult your orthodontist or dentist as soon as your retainer is broken. They can assess your situation and recommend a course of action to prevent significant movement of your teeth.",
